$interpreted: Yan-Bo: Hehe...yes. Especially delicious, this fruit is. Suited for treating an old friend, it is...
Law: Art thou sickly and in decline, or are ye merely feigning madness, Yan-Bo?

Law: In our younger years, we consumed 5 kilograms of red meat per day and liters of strong wine. We frightened even the cooks of the Alliance. 
And now thee speak of offering fruit?
Yan-Bo: Ah, recall that, I do. Not only juicy, this fruit is, but for making sweet wine, a superb—
Pang: Master Yan-Bo!
Pang: Pardon me, great masters.
Law: I didn't imagine I would encounter a member of the Tiger Tribe here.
Law: ...Have thee come here to train thy disciple?
Yan-Bo: No. Why you have come, Pang, I am aware. Compete with my old friend, you so desire. Yes?
Law: Eh?
Pang: Pang, at your service. I have seen the great master Law.
Law: And how dost thou know of me?
Pang: Your humble servant once served as the Guard of the Imperial Family in the Tiger Tribe. I heard the names of many great masters of the martial arts.
Pang: When I heard the descriptions of the residents of Maple Lake, I knew it was the Grandmaster they spoke of.
Law: A previous Guard of the Imperial Family...what brings thee here today? A traitor on the run, or banished from thine own land?
Pang: Your humble servant was irresolute, causing a sin of great magnitude, resulting in my banishment.
Law: Honesty and frankness are qualities one rarely encounters these days.
Law: Young lad, dost thou desire to battle?
Pang: If I may merely learn from the master, I would be ever so grateful. Meet a new friend in battle, and learn of their heart through their fists.
Law: Then let's learn of each other's heart!
Law: If thou so desire to learn, let us begin!
Pang: Yes, master! Your humble servant will put forth his utmost effort!
Yan-Bo: Ho, ho, ho...
Pang: Huff...huff...amazing...
Yan-Bo: Old friend, impeccable heights, your training has reached!
Law: Shut it! Who is this "old friend" you speak of?
Law: Young lad, are ye this old rat's disciple?
Pang: Um, I have still not had the honor. But one day, I shall change the great master's mind...
Law: Thine blows are unacceptable. Thou dost rely too strongly on thine power and physique. But ye sincerity in battle is commendable.
Pang: Great master, I am not worthy of such praise...
Yan-Bo: Hehe, Pang. A lie he cannot utter, my old friend. Take to heart his words of praise, you ought.
Pang: Many thanks, Master Law! Your humble servant shall not let you down!
Pang: I shall not disturb your reminiscing. Your servant shall leave at once!
Law: Ye dost see that in his fists lies thy shadow. Each move of thee, unveils to him a deeper understanding of the martial arts.
Yan-Bo: Gifted, he is. Taken in him as a disciple, I have not...
Law: Of course! Thou art not worthy to take in a disciple!
Law: Forgive my harsh words——
Yan-Bo: Speak the truth, you do. A grave sin, committed did I, those many years ago. Conceited, was I. A covetous desire to become a Grandmaster, that was.
Yan-Bo: Today, take in a student as my disciple, I dare not. Remember it all, I do. Old friend, anxious, be not.
Law: This was not my meaning!
Yan-Bo: ...Used to eating fruits, you are not. Check for some crackers in the cupboard, I shall.
Law: I said that's not what I meant! Yan-Bo! Don't thee dare flee again!
Law: Just as before, fleeing at the first sign of trouble.
Law: Speakth to me he does not, not a word does he utter. These reckless ways, how could he ever be one's master!?
Law: This is what I meant! Acting like taking in a disciple is easy!
Law: ...Casting away food so recklessly, just like during the drought...
Law: Eh, this branch has been broken in such an unnatural manner...
Law: ...A nasty odor that is.
Law: It appears...that it is not native to Maple Lake.
